 insight into my interesting world of family, cross and fun. After a few years of hemming and hawing, this blog also marks the begging of a brand new team for me...which of course makes me a bit more nervous.\r\n\r\nCheers to the start of a new season and getting rid of the nerves.', 'The Nerves Before the Storm', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '93-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-09-04 16:33:35', '2015-09-04 20:33:35', '', 93, 'http://therunup.com/uncategorized/93-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(97, 1, '2015-09-05 08:47:54', '2015-09-05 12:47:54', '', '954798_10203886130767795_8475714467792916131_n', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '954798_10203886130767795_8475714467792916131_n', '', '', '2015-09-05 08:47:54', '2015-09-05 12:47:54', '', 93, 'http://therunup.com/wp-content/uploads/954798_10203886130767795_8475714467792916131_n.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0),
(99, 1, '2015-09-10 19:30:30', '2015-09-10 23:30:30', 'The long awaited start of the cyclocross season kicked off this past Sunday with Granouge Cross in Delaware. I''ve only done this race a few time and all I remember about it is it''s hard and I usually have some bad luck. Since it was the only race before the UCI weekend in Trexlertown, I decided to go for it.\r\n\r\nThe course is on the DuPont property (yes, those DuPont''s) and provided a great mix of sharp, steep climbs and fast, bumpy descents. Over the years, Granouge grew to become on of the biggest UCI races in the mid-Atlantic region. After a minor hiatus, it has returned as more of a grassroots race. As a result, the course now includes some great wooded features.\r\n\r\nComing into the race I had no idea what to expect. I knew I wasn''t going to win, or podium, but I was hoping for a mid pack performance. I had two main goals: don''t crash and/or break my bike and ride as hard as I could, as long as I could. The latter would ultimately be my undoing.\r\n\r\nAs was the case last year, my starts are still not what they once were. It''s something I need to focus on and really figure out before I get into the meat of the season. As a result, I did a bit of chasing into the first section. From there, I began to pick people off one by one. In the first two laps I passed about 4 people and was trying to make my way up to the top 10 or so.\r\n\r\nAs we approached the midway point of the race, I decided to stick with where I was as I began to feel a little hot and fatigued. One lap later, my day was done.\r\n\r\nDid I push too hard? Did the heat and course take it''s toll on me? Is my fitness not 100% yet?\r\n\r\nThe easy answer is it''s probably a mix of everything, but the bottom line is for 40 minutes I raced above my expectations and felt great. The last 20 minutes involved me just pedaling and getting passed by virtually everyone. I''m honestly not sure where I finished and in a lot of ways I don''t care. These first 3 weeks of the season are going to be hard and I''m not going to hit primetime for at least another month. I pushed myself to my limit, didn''t crash or break anything and gained a little confidence. All in all, I would call it a good start to the season.\r\n\r\nThis weekend is one that I haven''t ever experienced. I''ve only done Nittany a few times and never at the UCI level. One of my season long goals is to finish on the lead lap of a UCI race. I think that''s a stretch for this weekend, but I''m going to ride like hell until I blow up or get pulled.\r\n\r\nNittany is like a grass crit with flat, wide open, stretches and a ton of corners you can hammer through. It rained all day today, which should help with the crazy dusty conditions I experienced at Granouge. It looks like despite the rain, Saturday should be dry. Sunday may be a bit more interesting...not to mention the stacked field both days.\r\n\r\nAs with last weekend, there''s only one way to find out what''s going to happen...', 'First Race of the Season: Granouge', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'first-race-of-the-season-granouge', '', '', '2015-09-10 17:30:49', '2015-09-10 21:30:49', '', 0, 'http://therunup.com/?p=99', 0, 'post', '', 1),
