(109, 1, '2015-09-18 16:59:07', '2015-09-18 20:59:07', 'This post is a little delayed due to my usual weekly hustle and bustle. Suddenly another race weekend is upon us, so I figured I''d give a quick post about the weekend that was.\r\n\r\nLast weekend I loaded up the van and drove all of 30 minutes to Nittany Cross. In addition to being the first two rounds of the MAC series, both races were UCI C2. As a result, the field was big and pretty well stacked. Honestly, it will probably be the toughest field I''ll face all season.\r\n\r\nSaturday turned from bad to worse as rain began to fall in the two hours leading up to our race. My first pre ride of the course was fast, railing each corner and powering through the straights. My second pre ride was filled with slick corners and increasingly soft straightaways. By race time the course became a perfect nightmare for me. I struggled with my start and was sliding all over the place in the corners. I ended up crashing 3 times including one where I slid face first, on my stomach, down a hill (like a penguin). The crowd loved that one. I lasted for 4 out of 8 laps before being pulled. I was frustrated because I felt like the conditions got the best of me and really wanted to make it one more lap.\r\n\r\nThe course dried up a bit for Sundays race and minus one massive mud pit, it seemed much more to my liking. During warm ups I noticed the Elite Women turning 7 minute laps. A quick judge of math based on the quality of our field meant near 6 minute laps for the leaders and no rest for us mere mortals. I actually had a decent start, but missed judged the mud pit on my second lap and lost contact with a group. Whether it''s fitness, skill, or luck, I was unable to make it back and tried to settle into a rhythm. I wasn''t ever able to really settle in for some reason and with 5 to go they pulled me. I made it 4 laps again, but was disappointed I didn''t make it 5 or 6.\r\n\r\nAfter a few days of thinking and looking at it, I''m actually walking away with my head held high. I did lose ground to some guys who I feel like I shouldn''t have, but I also made it more then halfway through two tough UCI races. It''s just September and I have a long road a head of me before Nationals. I definitely raced as hard as I could on Sunday and I actually had a non horrific start. It''s about a month before another planned UCI weekend, so plenty of time to get stronger and faster.\r\n\r\nThis weekend I return to one of my favorite races and one that gave me a lot of motivation last year, Town Hall. It''s a PACX race and a great course. It features one hell of a climb and a lot of fast descents and quick turns. I''m hoping to finish on the lead lap like I did last year and really hoping to have a group to ride with. I have no points in the series since I skipped the first race, so a back row start is where I will begin. On the bright side, the filed is one of the biggest I''ve seen at a PACX race. I noticed a few heavy hitters signed up, so things will be interesting. It will be hot and dry like Granouge and my plan will be the same: ride as hard as I can for as long as I can.\r\n\r\nThe biggest bonus is the whole family is coming tomorrow, so I will have extra motivation and fun.\r\n\r\nOne final note - thanks to all who cheered for me this weekend. Riding DFL is tough and sucks, you guys made it better.', 'A Painful UCI Weekend', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '107-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-09-18 16:59:07', '2015-09-18 20:59:07', '', 107, 'http://therunup.com/uncategorized/107-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
